                                                                                                   Ⓐⓡⓡⓐⓨ
↬ An array in Java is a data structure that stores multiple values of the same data type in a single variable.
↬ Arrays are fixed in size once created and are indexed starting from 0.

Types of Arrays in Java
• Java mainly supports:
➦ One-Dimensional Array
➦ Multi-Dimensional Array (2D, 3D, etc.)


★ One-Dimensional Array
An array is used to store many values of the same type in one variable.
Example:-
int a, b, c, d;
int[] a;
// A one-dimensional array stores values in a single line.
Index:  0   1   2   3   4
Value: 10  20  30  40  50

↬ Create a One-Dimensional Array 
int[] numbers; //Declaration
numbers = new int[5];  //Memory Allocation
numbers[0] = 10; //Store Values
numbers[1] = 20;  
numbers[2] = 30;
numbers[3] = 40;
numbers[4] = 50;
OR
↬ Shortcut Method to 
int[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
 ➱ How to access array element:-
System.out.println(numbers[0]); // 10
System.out.println(numbers[3]); // 40

● Example 1: Print Array Values
public class ArrayDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

        for (int i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
            System.out.println(numbers[i]);
        
    }
}
✔ // Output =5

◦ Advantages
➣ Easy to use
➣ Fast access using index
➣ Less code compared to variables

◦ Disadvantages
➣ Fixed size
➣ Cannot store different data types
➣ No built-in methods like ArrayList

◦ Very Important
➣ Index starts from 0
➣ ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException occurs if index is wrong
➣ Size is fixed at creation time


